# get rid of outliers
mean_ad <- mean(df$admissions, na.rm = TRUE)
sd_ad <- sd(df$admissions, na.rm = TRUE)
z_score <- (df$admissions-mean_ad)/sd_ad
nrow(df)
## [1] 92907
#identify outliers with z_score > 3, in case to be removed for better analysis performance(less variance)
summary(z_score)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
## -0.3336 -0.3176 -0.2777  0.0000 -0.1102 22.4920
nrow(df[-which(abs(z_score) > 3), ])
## [1] 91099
filtered.df <- df[-which(abs(z_score) > 3), ]
names(filtered.df)[names(filtered.df) == 'county_of_program_location'] <- "county_name"
names(filtered.df)
## [1] "year"                    "county_name"

## spot check distribution of admissions categorized by different groups

## Admission count by age group
aggregate(admissions ~ age_group, filtered.df, sum) %>% arrange(desc(admissions)) %>% mutate(age_group = fct_reorder(age_group, admissions, .desc = TRUE)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = age_group, y = admissions)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = age_group), stat = "identity") +
  ylab("count") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "age_group") +
  labs(title = "Admission count by age group", x = "Year", y = "Total") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))

## Admission count by year, county, program_category
aggregate(admissions ~ year + county_name + program_category, filtered.df, sum) %>%
   ggplot(aes(x=year, y=admissions)) +
   geom_line(aes(col = county_name, group = county_name)) +
   labs(title = "Admission count by year, county, program_category", x = "Year", y = "Total") +
   theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
   scale_x_discrete(breaks=seq(2007, 2020, 4)) +
   facet_wrap(~ program_category)

## Admission count by year and primary substance group

# create county tibble by retrieving only unique county_name values
## import meta data for retreiving county code
meta <- read.csv("New_York_State_ZIP_Codes-County_FIPS_Cross-Reference.csv")
## subset meta data to get unique county code
code_name <- meta %>% select(County.Name, County.Code) %>% unique() 

## check dimension
dim(code_name)
## [1] 62  2
## retrieve unique county names
county_name <- filtered.df$county_name %>% unique()
length(county_name) # no "Hamilton"
## [1] 61
# filter county code corresponding to county name Hamilton
code <- code_name %>% filter(County.Name != "Hamilton") %>% select(County.Code)
# check again
dim(code)
## [1] 61  1
#rename col name
colnames(code) <- "county_code"
county <- data.frame(county_code=code, county_name=county_name)

# create program_category tibble by retrieving only unique program_category values
program_cat <- filtered.df$program_category %>% unique()
program_code <- c("CR", "IP", "OTR", "OP", "RE", "SP")
program_category <- data.frame(program_code = program_code,
                               program_category = program_cat)

# create primary_sub_group tibble by retrieving only unique primary_sub_group values
primary_sub_group <- filtered.df$primary_substance_group %>% unique()
substance_code <- c("H", "AC", "AO", "OP", "CA", "MA", "NO")
primary_substance_group <- data.frame(substance_code=substance_code, primary_substance_group = primary_sub_group)

# using inner join to combine all tibbles by primary key and value pair. only pairs matched in both tibbles will be combined and joined
admissions_data <- inner_join(filtered.df, county, by = "county_name") %>% inner_join(program_category, by = "program_category") %>% inner_join(primary_substance_group, by = "primary_substance_group") %>% select(year, county_code, program_code, service_type, age_group, substance_code, admissions) %>% arrange(year, county_code)
admissions_data$substance_code <- as.factor(admissions_data$substance_code)
admissions_data$program_code <- as.factor(admissions_data$program_code)
admissions_data$county_code %>% unique()

# create function to aggregate totoal admissions by year and plot line graph
annualAdmissions <- function(df) {
  admision_year.df <- df %>% group_by(year) %>% select(year, admissions) %>% summarize(total = n())
  return(admision_year.df)
}
annualAdmissions(admissions_data)
## # A tibble: 14 × 2
##    year  total

# plot line graph to display distribution of admissions per year, check the trend
annualAdmissions(admissions_data) %>% ggplot(aes(x = year, y = total, group = 1)) +
  geom_line(color = "Red") +
  labs(title = "Admission count by year", x = "Year", y = "Total") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  annotate(geom="text", x = "2019", y = 6834, label = "The highest number of admissions") +
  annotate(geom="point", x = "2019", y = 6834, size=5, shape=21)

## there is slight gradual increase from 2009-2012, a gradual decreave over 4 years since after. Following 2 years a steep increase and kindly level off reaching highest admissions in 2019 to6834, and a significant decrease in 2020

# plot bar graph of top 10 admissions proportion by counties. 
inner_join(admissions_data, county, by = "county_code") %>% select(admissions, county_name) %>% group_by(county_name) %>% summarize(total =n()) %>% arrange(desc(total)) %>% top_n(10) %>% mutate(county_name = fct_reorder(county_name, total, .desc = TRUE)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = county_name, y = total)) + geom_bar(aes(y = total/sum(total), fill = county_name), stat = "identity") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "county") +
  labs(title = "Admission proportion by top 10 counties", x = "County", y = "Admission Proportion") +
   scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent) +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5))
## Selecting by total

## New York stands out as far more admission rate and rest 9 counties has similar percentage ranging from 8-10%

df_rehab <- admissions_data[which(str_detect(admissions_data$service_type, "([R|r]ehab)")), ]

## check if service type contains only rehab
df_rehab$service_type %>% unique()
## [1] "Inpatient Rehabilitation"          "Outpatient Rehabilitation"        
## [3] "Residential Rehab for Youth"       "Specialized Services Outpt Rehab" 
## [5] "Stabilization Rehab Reintegration" "Rehab and Reintegration"          
## [7] "Stabilization and Rehab"           "Residential Rehabilitation"
# which substance is most prominent by age group
df_rehab %>% group_by(age_group, substance_code) %>% summarize(total = n()) %>% arrange(desc(total)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = reorder(age_group, order(total, decreasing = T)), y = total)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = substance_code), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
   labs(title = "substance count by age group", x = "Age group", y = "Count") +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Substance code", labels = c("AC=Alcohol", "AO=All Others", "CA=Cocaine incl Crack", "H=Heroin", "MA=Marijuana incl Hashish", "OP=Other Opioids"))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'age_group'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

## under 18 admissions are mostly fewer than 250; 18-24 group has most Marijuana and a bit fewer are alcohol and Heroin;
## 25-34 shows a more evenly spread admissions per substance with more in alcohol; 35-44 and 45-54 have similar distribution having cocaine and heroin on top; 55 plus alcohol takes the lead

## extra plot showing which program category is most prominent by age group
df_rehab %>% group_by(age_group, program_code) %>% summarize(total = n()) %>% arrange(desc(total)) %>% ggplot(aes(x = reorder(age_group, order(total, decreasing = T)), y = total)) + geom_bar(aes(fill = program_code), stat = "identity", position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "program category count by age group", x = "Age group", y = "Count") +
  ylim(c(0,3000)) +
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "program code", labels = c("IP"="Inpatient", "OP"="Outpatient", "RE"="Residential", "SP"="Specialized"))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'age_group'. You can override using the `.groups` argument.

## i can conclude that age under 18 may not that serious or to an extent to be inpatient while other groups show opposite situation.

#inner join rehab df and county tibbles to have county name in tibble
df_rehab_county_sub <- inner_join(df_rehab, county, by = "county_code")
# line plot showing admissions by year and substance facetted by counties
aggregate(admissions ~ year + county_name + substance_code, df_rehab_county_sub, sum) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=admissions, group = substance_code)) +
  geom_line(aes(col=substance_code)) +
  labs(title = "Admission count by year, county, substance_code", x = "Year", y = "Total") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=seq(2007, 2020, 4)) +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Substance code", labels = c("AC=Alcohol", "AO=All Others", "CA=Cocaine incl Crack", "H=Heroin", "MA=Marijuana incl Hashish", "OP=Other Opioids")) +
  facet_wrap(~ county_name)

# with bar plot 
aggregate(admissions ~ year + county_name + substance_code, df_rehab_county_sub, sum) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year, y=admissions, group = substance_code)) +
  geom_col(aes(fill=substance_code), position = "dodge") +
  labs(title = "Admission count by year, county, substance_code", x = "Year", y = "Total") +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5)) +
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=seq(2007, 2020, 4)) +
  scale_color_discrete(name = "Substance code", labels = c("AC=Alcohol", "AO=All Others", "CA=Cocaine incl Crack", "H=Heroin", "MA=Marijuana incl Hashish", "OP=Other Opioids")) +
  facet_wrap(~ county_name)

## Consistent with what trend Q5 shows about top 10 counties of admission count and add another layer by substance distribution in each county by year. Alcohol remains almost top in top 10 counties, the rest counties are hard to be seen, and some are broken lines or no values shown in line plot for some years. the next are cocaine and marijuana seen in top 10 counties as well.
